## Error Analysis

The build fails during the brp-suse post-install sanity check (`brp-25-symlink`):

```
ERROR: link target doesn't exist (neither in build root nor in installed system):
  /bin/gawk -> usr/bin/gawk
```

**Root cause:** The `%files` section lists `/bin/gawk` as a file. In modern SUSE (usrmerge), there is no separate `/bin` — it's always `/usr/bin`. When RPM processes the spec, `%{_bindir}` expands to `/usr/bin`, so `ln -s %{_bindir}/gawk %{buildroot}/bin/gawk` creates a symlink at `/bin/gawk -> /usr/bin/gawk`. The brp-suse script then rejects this because `/bin` doesn't exist as a real directory.

The previous attempt (Attempt 4) attempted to remove the `%if !0%{?usrmerged}` block but apparently left the `%files` entry referencing `/bin/gawk`, or the change didn't fully take effect.

## Fix Needed

1. **In the `%install` section:** Remove the `ln -s %{_bindir}/gawk %{buildroot}/bin/gawk` line (the conditional block around it should have already been removed). This symlink is unnecessary on usrmerge systems — `/usr/bin/gawk` exists directly after `make install`.

2. **In the `%files` section:** Change the entry from `/bin/gawk` to `/usr/bin/gawk`. The `%{_bindir}` macro expands correctly, so use that instead of hardcoding `/bin/`.